Now follow below method based on your machine:
-------------------------------------------------------------


For Linux, You need to configure the local GIT client with a username and email address,

$ git config --global user.name "blockchain99"
$ git config --global user.email "shinebytheriver@yahoo.com"
$ git config -l
Once GIT is configured, we can begin using it to access GitHub. Example :

---------------------------------
$ git clone https://github.com/blockchain99/fullstack-web.git
> Cloning into `fullstack-web`...
> Warning:  warning "You appear to have cloned an empty repository"?
* solution : --------------sol --------
Once you have cloned your (empty) repository, you still need to:
add files in the local folder created by the git clone command.
type
:

$ git add .
$ git commit -m "First batch of files"
$ git push -u origin master


=> 
$ git push
fatal: No configured push destination.
Either specify the URL from the command-line or configure a remote repository using

    git remote add <name> <url>
$ git remote add origin https://github.com/blockchain99/fullstack-web.git 

and then push using the remote name

    git push <name>
$ git push origin

--------------------------end of sol-------------

$ Username for 'https://github.com' : blockchain99
$ Password for 'https://github.com' : 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
                                      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
Now cache the given record in your computer to remembers the token : 

$ git config --global credential.helper cache

If needed, anytime you can delete the cache record by :

$ git config --global --unset credential.helper
$ git config --system --unset credential.helper
Now try to pull with -v to verify

$ git pull -v

=========================
below is used to a add a new remote:

$ git remote add origin git@github.com:blockchain99/fullstack-web.git   (It works!!)
below is used to change the url of an existing remote repository:

$ git remote set-url origin git@github.com:blockchain99/fullstack-web.git
below will push your code to the master branch of the remote repository defined with origin and -u let you point your current local branch to the remote master branch:

$ git push -u origin master

